    {
      "content": "{\"claim\": \"A shift in maritime technology to the brailed sail enabled Sea Peoples fleets to navigate against prevailing winds and launch coordinated surprise attacks on Mycenaean, Hittite, Ugaritic and Levantine coastal centers during previously safe sailing seasons, precipitating their collapse.\", \"mechanism\": \"nautical innovation enabling off-season maritime raiding\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Mycenaean Greece\", \"Hittite Anatolia\", \"Ugarit\", \"Levantine city‑states\"], \"excludes\": [\"Egypt\", \"Cyprus\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Iconographic and shipwreck evidence shows brailed sails appearing only after 1100 BCE, well after the destruction layers dated 1200–1150 BCE at the four societies\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"Analytical matrix compares the earliest depictions of brailed-sail vessels, the seasonality of destruction evidence, and the tactical surprise indicators across the four societies.\"}"
